
“When your team evaluates whether an AI feature is working, what does that process actually 
look like right now and what is missing from it?”

The pattern across almost every reply: evals happen after the fact, 
run by the PM alone, and never reach engineering or leadership in a format anyone can act on. The most common missing piece was a rubric
that the whole team agrees on before the sprint starts , not after the feature ships and something breaks.


The first breakdown: evaluating the wrong thing.

Most teams measure model accuracy. That is a model metric.

The PM’s job is to measure product outcomes , whether the user made a better decision faster because of the feature. Accuracy is an input.

Decision quality is the output. Most evals stop at the input.


The second breakdown: no baseline.

A feature that improves response time by 40% sounds impressive until you learn the baseline was manual copy-paste into a spreadsheet.

The 40% improvement is real , but the comparison that makes it meaningful was never defined.

Without a baseline established before the sprint, your eval numbers are just numbers. They do not tell anyone what changed.


The third breakdown: evals happen after the problem is visible.

By the time most teams run a proper eval, the feature has been live for six weeks and the trust erosion signal from Module 05 is already in the data.

A pre-launch eval with agreed criteria would have caught the failure mode in staging.

The post-launch eval is more expensive to act on and almost always produces a reactive fix rather than a structural one.

